<div class="card card-var">
  <h3>Variance: Measuring the Spread</h3>
  <p><strong>Variance</strong> tells you how far each value is from the mean, on average. Higher variance = more spread out.</p>

  <div class="formula-box" style="border-color:var(--var-green);">
    <div style="font-family:'Fredoka One',cursive;font-size:16px;color:var(--var-green);">Variance Formula</div>
    <div class="formula" style="color:var(--var-green);">Variance = Σ(each value − mean)² ÷ n</div>
    <div class="explain">
      1. Find the mean<br>
      2. Subtract the mean from each value (the "deviation")<br>
      3. Square each deviation (removes negatives)<br>
      4. Average all the squared deviations
    </div>
  </div>

  <div style="background:rgba(16,185,129,0.08);border:2px solid rgba(16,185,129,0.25);border-radius:12px;padding:20px;margin:20px 0;">
    <strong style="color:var(--var-green);font-size:17px;">Worked Example: Data = [2, 4, 4, 4, 5, 5, 7, 9]</strong>
    <div class="step-trace" style="margin-top:14px;">
      <div class="step active"><div class="step-num" style="color:var(--var-green);">1</div><div><strong>Mean:</strong> (2+4+4+4+5+5+7+9) ÷ 8 = 40 ÷ 8 = <strong style="color:var(--var-green);">5.0</strong></div></div>
      <div class="step active"><div class="step-num" style="color:var(--var-green);">2</div><div><strong>Deviations:</strong> (2−5)=-3, (4−5)=-1, -1, -1, (5−5)=0, 0, (7−5)=2, (9−5)=4</div></div>
      <div class="step active"><div class="step-num" style="color:var(--var-green);">3</div><div><strong>Squared:</strong> 9, 1, 1, 1, 0, 0, 4, 16</div></div>
      <div class="step active"><div class="step-num" style="color:var(--var-green);">4</div><div><strong>Average:</strong> (9+1+1+1+0+0+4+16) ÷ 8 = 32 ÷ 8 = <strong style="color:var(--var-green);">4.0</strong></div></div>
    </div>
    <div style="text-align:center;margin-top:14px;font-family:'Fredoka One',cursive;font-size:22px;color:var(--var-green);">Variance = 4.0</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="card card-var">
  <h3>Standard Deviation: Variance Made Friendly</h3>
  <p>Variance is in <strong>squared units</strong> (like "points²"), which is hard to interpret. <strong>Standard Deviation (σ)</strong> is just the <strong>square root of variance</strong> — it brings us back to the original units!</p>

  <div class="formula-box" style="border-color:var(--var-green);">
    <div style="font-family:'Fredoka One',cursive;font-size:16px;color:var(--var-green);">Standard Deviation</div>
    <div class="formula" style="color:var(--var-green);">Std Dev = √Variance</div>
    <div class="explain">
      From our example: Std Dev = √4.0 = <strong style="color:#fff;">2.0</strong><br>
      This means values are <strong style="color:#fff;">typically about 2 points</strong> away from the mean (5)
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="code-line">import statistics

data = [2, 4, 4, 4, 5, 5, 7, 9]

# Population variance & std dev (use all data)
print("Variance:", statistics.pvariance(data))     # 4.0
print("Std Dev:", statistics.pstdev(data))          # 2.0

# Sample variance & std dev (divides by n-1)
print("Sample Var:", statistics.variance(data))     # 4.57
print("Sample SD:", statistics.stdev(data))         # 2.14

# Using pandas
import pandas as pd
s = pd.Series(data)
print("Pandas Std:", round(s.std(), 2))             # 2.14</div>

  <div class="output-console">Variance: 4.0
Std Dev: 2.0
Sample Var: 4.571428571428571
Sample SD: 2.138089935299395
Pandas Std: 2.14</div>

  <div class="tip-box tip-box-var">📊 <strong>Population vs Sample:</strong> Use <code>pvariance/pstdev</code> when you have ALL the data. Use <code>variance/stdev</code> (divides by n-1) when you have a <em>sample</em> from a bigger population. Pandas uses sample (n-1) by default!</div>
</div>

<div class="card card-var">
  <h3>What Does Standard Deviation Actually Tell You?</h3>

